menu_description.describe: Describe column's values (Top unique values, Min, Max, Sum, STD, Var,...)
menu_description.filter: Defining custom Filtering for the main spreadsheet, Charts, ...
menu_description.build: Creating new column(s) or alter current columns using dataframe functions
menu_description.reshape: Create a new grid using either PIVOT table, Aggregations w/ GroupBy or Transpose.
menu_description.charts: Plot chart (line, bar, scatter, pie, wordcloud,...)
menu_description.heatmap: Presenting heatmap for numerical values in the main table. 'Overall' will calculate over the min/max of every column whereas 'By Col' will calculate each column individually by its min/max.
menu_description.highlight_dtypes: Highlight columns based on pandas dtypes. For dtype's name hover the mouse over column name.
menu_description.highlight_missing: Highlight any cells which contain "nan" values (or in the case of strings, empty strings or strings consisting only of spaces). Also, a "!" will be prepended to any column header which contains missing values.
menu_description.highlight_outliers: Highlight any cells for numeric columns which surpass the upper or lower bounds of a custom outlier computation. Lower bounds outliers will be on a red scale and upper bounds outliers will be on a blue scale. Also, a "★" will be prepended to any column header which contains outliers.
menu_description.highlight_range: Highlight any cells for numeric columns which match any of the filters for equals, greater than or less than. Click "Highlight Range" to update filters.
menu_description.instances: Show existing datasets loaded to D-Tale.
menu_description.code: Code snippet of commands performed upon your data to produce this grid.
menu_description.export: Download DataFrame as CSV, TSV, Parquet or HTML
menu_description.about: Link to the source code repository, documentation
menu_description.shutdown: Close D-Tale and all other open datasets without save. Do you want to export DataFrame?
menu_description.logout: Authentication is activated on D-Tale. This will log you out of your current session and redirect you to the login screen.
menu_description.editing: Update cells to anything you'd like. Press "Enter" to confirm or "Esc" to exit. Invalid types will throw errors. Protected values are "nan" & "inf".
menu_description.bool_editing: Update cells to anything you'd like. Press "Enter" to confirm or "Esc" to exit. Press "n" to set value to "nan".
menu_description.xarray_conversion: Convert your pandas.Dataframe to an xarray.Dataset by selecting columns as an index. Once this is complete you'll be able to view different slices of your data by choosing index values.
menu_description.upload: Load CSV/TSV files, CSV/TSV/JSON from the web or sample datasets to D-Tale using pandas.read_csv(), pandas.read_json() or customized loaders.
menu_description.duplicates: Remove duplicate columns/values from your data as well as extract duplicates out into separate instances.
menu_description.theme: Toggle between light & dark themes for your viewing pleasure (only affects grid, not popups or charts).
menu_description.pps: PPS is an asymmetric, data-type-agnostic score that can detect linear or non-linear relationships between two columns. The score ranges from 0 (no predictive power) to 1 (perfect predictive power). It can be used as an alternative to the correlation (matrix). WARNING: This could take a while to load.
menu_description.network: If you're currently viewing data containing information for a directed graph then try feeding it into our "Network Viewer"
menu_description.reload_data: Force a reload of the data from the server for the current rows being viewing in the grid by clicking this button. This can be helpful when viewing the grid from within another application like jupyter or nested within another website.
menu_description.merge: Merge & Stack (concatenate vertically) dataframes currently loaded into D-Tale or upload additional ones for that purpose.
menu_description.low_variance_1: Show flags on column headers where both these conditions are true:
menu_description.low_variance_2: Count of unique values / column size < 10%
menu_description.low_variance_3: Count of most common value / Count of second most common value > 20
menu_description.low_variance_4: You can view variance information by clicking the "Variance" option in the column menu.
menu_description.xarray_dim_des: View individual xarray dimensions. You are currently viewing:
menu_description.pin_menu: Toggle for pinning this menu to the left side of the screen.
menu_description.language: Choose which language to use when displaying the majority of text in D-Tale. Choose between english (EN), chinese (CN) or portuguese (PT). The default is english.
menu_description.clear_data: Remove this data from memory. If this is the only data loaded into memory then you will be redirected to the "Load Data" screen.
menu_description.open_process: There are multiple pieces of data loaded into memory, switch the UI to this data.
menu_description.missingno: Analyze the presence of missing data (NaN) using the "missingno" package.
menu_description.predefined_filters: Apply any "Predefined Filters" to your data. You would have loaded these using the "dtale.predefined_filters.set_filters" or "dtale.predefined_filters.add_filters" functions.
menu_description.max_width: Rebuild the widths of the cells in the grid and set a maximum width in pixels. Any column that exceeds this width will be truncated to this size (you can still drag the column to be wider) anything else remains unchanged. Any cell that exceeds this maximum will have a tooltip available on hover to view the full value.
menu_description.max_height: Rebuild the heights of the cells in the grid and set a maximum height in pixels.
menu_description.show_all_heatmap: Show all non-numeric columns when displaying heatmap highlighting.
menu_description.corr_analysis: Remove columns (features) based on their correlations with other columns in your dataset. If there is a strong correlation amongst some columns (features) then maybe they aren't relevant to keep around?
menu_description.gage_rnr: A Gage R&R is a scientific study that falls under the larger topic of Measurement System Analysis (MSA). When you observe any measurement, it will typically vary from time to time. That variation in the observed measurement will be the result of the variation in the object that you are measuring plus the variation of the measuring device.
menu_description.timeseries_analysis: Analyze time series data using different "statsmodels.tsa" functions
menu_description.hide_header_editor: If checked, hides the header editor when editing cells in the grid
menu_description.arcticdb: Load data from a specific library & symbol in ArcticDB
menu_description.jump_to_column: For wide dataframes, you can shrink the columns displayed down to what is locked and a column selected from a dropdown.

builders.Name: Name
builders.numeric: Add, subtract, multiply or divide two columns of numeric data or static numeric values.
builders.string: Concatenate columns together to form a string.
builders.bins: Convert numeric data into bins using pandas cut or qcut functions.
builders.datetime: Pull out properties (minute, hour, time...) or convert to date representations (month-end, month-start, year-end...) using datatime columns.
builders.encoder: Encode categorical data as indicators using OneHotEncoder, OrdinalEncoder, LabelEncoder or FeatureHasher.
builders.random: Build a column of random data for different data types using range rules.
builders.similarity: Calculate string similarity distances between two columns using one of the following  algorithms: Levenshtein, Damerau-Leveneshtein, Jaro-Winkler, Jaccard Index.
builders.standardize: Standardize a numeric column for outliers using one of the following scalars from sklearn: RobustScalar, QuantileTransformer, PowerTransformer.
builders.type_conversion: Convert columns of one type to another.
builders.transform: Transform numeric data of one column by grouping on others and applying an aggregation (sum, mean, count...).
builders.winsorize: Remove outliers in your column by replacing values that fall at or below the lowest percentile with the maximum value in that group and replacing values that fall at or above highest percentile with the minimum value of that group.
builders.zscore_normalize: Normalize a numeric column by turning it into z-scores. Simply subtract it's mean and divide by it's standard deviation.
builders.cumsum: Calculate the cumulative sum of a column.
builders.cleaning: Clean string data of punctuation, numbers & other erroneous data using different functions.
builders.diff: Calculate differences between rows using Pandas` diff() function.
builders.data_slope: Calculate the slope (sequential increases/decreases) of a column based on the current order.
builders.rolling: Run a smoother computation (mean, max, min) on numeric data by using pandas' rolling (moving) function.
builders.exponential_smoothing: Create a column using exponential smoothing which assigns exponentially decreasing weights as the observation get older
builders.shift: Shift index by desired number of periods
builders.expanding: Provide expanding transformations for a column
builders.substring: Extract substring from string column by specifying start and end indices.
builders.split: Split a string column by a sequence of characters into additional columns.
builders.concatenate: Concatenate columns with raw strings or other columns to create a new string column.
builders.resample: Resample timeseries data into different periods
builders.No conversion mappings available for dty: No conversion mappings available for dtype
builders.Add Space Between Word and Numbers: Add Space Between Word and Numbers
builders.Update Space Values to Empty String: Update Space Values to Empty String
builders.drop_multispace: Replace sequences of multiple spaces in the rows i.e. "Foo    Bar" > "Foo Bar"
builders.drop_punctuation: Remove punctuation characters !"#$%&'|()*+,-./:;<=>?@[]^_`{|}~ from the text. i.e. "foo." > "foo"
builders.stopwords: Remove a user-defined stop words from rows by entering a comma-separated string of stop words below
builders.nltk_stopwords: Remove stop words based on NLTK library
builders.drop_numbers: Remove numbers from the content. i.e. "Foo123" > "Foo"
builders.keep_alpha: Remove characters which are not part of the standard alphabet or spaces. i.e. "BÀr. @123 foo" > "BÀrfoo"
builders.normalize_accents: Normalize accent characters with normal characters i.e. "BÀr foö" > "BAr foo'"
builders.drop_all_space: Remove all spaces in the row i.e. "New York" > "NewYork"
builders.add_word_number_space: Add space between words and/or numbers. i.e. "Berlin123" > "Berlin 123"
builders.drop_repeated_chars: Removes characters which are repeated within a value i.e. "BBerlin" > "Berlin"
builders.hidden_chars: Removes characters that cannot be printed to your screen using string.printable
builders.replace_hyphen_w_space: Replaces any hyphens (unicode or otherwise) with a space

timeseries.lamb_desc: The Hodrick-Prescott smoothing parameter. A value of 1600 is suggested for quarterly data. Ravn and Uhlig suggest using a value of 6.25 (1600/4**4) for annual data and 129600 (1600*3**4) for monthly data.
timeseries.low_desc: Minimum period for oscillations, ie., Baxter and King suggest that the Burns-Mitchell U.S. business cycle has 6 for quarterly data and 1.5 for annual data.
timeseries.high_desc: Maximum period for oscillations BK suggest that the U.S. business cycle has 32 for quarterly data and 8 for annual data.
timeseries.K_desc: Lead-lag length of the filter. Baxter and King propose a truncation length of 12 for quarterly data and 3 for annual data.
timeseries.drift_desc: Whether or not to remove a trend from the data. The trend is estimated as np.arange(nobs)*(x[-1] - x[0])/(len(x)-1).

export.rows_desc: Your dataset contains more than 10,000 rows. I would advise selecting a subset of rows (or editing your filters further).  Setting a value above will take the top N rows from your dataset.
